{
  "texts": [
    "When discussing two-source extractors, we will refer to the input X as the extractor input and Y as the weak seed.",
    "In the case that Y is already near-perfectly random, we will simply call it the seed.",
    "Definition 7 (Seeded randomness extractor).",
    "A seeded extractor is a special case (n1, k 1, n 2, k 2 = n 2, m, ϵ)-two-source randomness extractor, where k 2 = n 2.We have mentioned that our extractors are strong, and now we define this propertyDefinition 8 (Strong randomness extractor).",
    "A (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, ϵ)-randomness extractor Ext: X ∈ {0, 1} n 1 × Y ∈ {0, 1} n 2 → {0, 1} m is strong in the input Y if, ∆([Ext(X, Y), Y], [U m, Y]) ≤ ϵ (9) or quantum-proof strong in the input Y if ∆ Q ([Ext(X, Y), Y], [U m, Y]) ≤ ϵ, (10)where U m denotes the uniform distribution over m bits."
  ]
}